          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">After a miserable M=
ay at the box office, Hollywood=E2=80=99s hopes seem pinned on Sony=E2=80=
=99s <i>Bad Boys: Ride or Die</i>, the <b>Will Smith </b>and <b>Martin Lawr=
ence </b>action sequel out June 7=E2=80=94and the latest faux tentpole in a=
 summer filled with them. But executives won=E2=80=99t only be concerned wi=
th the actual <i>performance</i> of a franchise whose most recent entry deb=
uted to $72 million over the long President=E2=80=99s Day weekend in early =
2020, right before Covid shut down the world. They=E2=80=99ll also be close=
ly following how <i>Ride or Die</i> performs against its $50 million-$55 mi=
llion tracking for opening weekend.<br/><br/>This year=E2=80=99s bummer sum=
mer seems all the worse because prerelease tracking has been off for three =
of the most recent tentpole weekends. For example, <i>The Fall Guy </i>was =
projected to debut with $35 million but came in just under
$28 million. Two weeks later, <i>IF </i>debuted not to $40 million as proje=
cted but $33.7 million. But tracking, which has never been a perfect scienc=
e, appears to be bearing too much weight <i>this summer</i> as a chew toy f=
or Hollywood=E2=80=99s collective anxiety. <br/><br/>As for why tracking do=
esn=E2=80=99t always match up with the opening weekend grosses, sometimes i=
t=E2=80=99s a review embargo dropping days before release, or underestimati=
ng the potential for films starring, or targeted at, underrepresented demog=
raphics. (That longtime issue became a running joke amid <b>Tyler Perry</b>=
=E2=80=99s mid-2000s peak.) Sometimes, the tracking and the armchair pundit=
s are just wrong; a result, increasingly, of media types ensconced in their=
 own fandom-focused bubbles. Projecting <i>The Wolverine </i>to open with $=
65 million-$80 million in 2013 never made sense. It was a solo <b>Hugh Jack=
man</b>-led comic book drama with little else to sell, following up the mos=
tly disliked <i>X-Men Origins:
Wolverine </i>(which opened to $85 million in May 2009). And so its $53 mil=
lion launch was seen as a box office failure, even when it was mainly a tra=
cking failure.<br/></td>
         </tr>
